<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,582,750]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,654,679]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ros-Farre &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2013" box="[335,571,654,678]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Aspicera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buffingtoni">
<emphasis box="[335,571,654,678]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Aspicera buffingtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dalla Torre" authorityYear="1889" box="[745,859,654,678]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Aspicera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hartigi">
<emphasis box="[745,859,654,678]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">A. hartigi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both having scutellar foveae with at least two longitudinal carinae that continue onto scutellar disc, scutellar pits very deep. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dalla Torre" authorityYear="1889" box="[1068,1176,691,715]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Aspicera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hartigi">
<emphasis box="[1068,1176,691,715]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">A. hartigi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
scutum is transversely carinate while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ros-Farre &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2013" box="[344,492,726,750]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Aspicera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buffingtoni">
<emphasis box="[344,492,726,750]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">A.buffingtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is coriaceous.
</paragraph>
